.TH SINGINE-SNAPSHOT 1 "2026-03-17" "singine 0.2.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
singine-snapshot \- persist a full Singine runtime, server, and Logseq context snapshot
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B singine snapshot save
[\fB--output\fR \fIPATH\fR]
[\fB--host\fR \fIHOST\fR]
[\fB--port\fR \fIPORT\fR]
[\fB--environment-type\fR \fIlocal|edge|docker\fR]
[\fB--logseq-url\fR \fIURL\fR]
[\fB--logseq-token\fR \fITOKEN\fR]
[\fB--json\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B snapshot
command writes one JSON file that captures the current Singine operating
context:
.IP \(bu 2
runtime shell and Python metadata
.IP \(bu 2
server defaults and route URLs
.IP \(bu 2
docker packaging files
.IP \(bu 2
git branch, HEAD, and working tree excerpt
.IP \(bu 2
Java activity interfaces and taxonomy path
.IP \(bu 2
publication and migration paths for Ant, xmldoclet, SilkPage, and generated spec output
.IP \(bu 2
Logseq API defaults and fallback path
.PP
This is the simplest way to save the entire context in Singine for later
inspection, issue reports, or migration planning. The saved activity metadata
includes recursively discovered JVM packages such as
\fIsingine.activity.photo\fR, so publication and review workflows are preserved
with the rest of the runtime state.
.SH DEFAULT OUTPUT
.IP
\fI~/.singine/context/latest.json\fR
.SH EXAMPLES
.nf
singine snapshot save
singine snapshot save --json
singine snapshot save --output /tmp/singine-context.json --environment-type docker --json
.fi
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR singine (1),
.BR singine-context (1),
.BR singine-runtime (1),
.BR singine-server (1),
.BR singine-logseq (1)
